| Beyond the formal, often drawn-out debates, editors are also afforded the option to formally propose the deletion of a page. This is typically done when they harbor the optimistic belief that its removal would be an entirely uncontroversial affair, a quiet, almost unnoticed slide into digital oblivion. Then, there's the swift, decisive, and frankly, often brutal, action of speedy deletion. This particular mechanism is reserved for those exceptionally clear-cut circumstances where a page so flagrantly violates [strict criteria](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion)—criteria that have themselves been established by prior consensus—that any further discussion would simply be a waste of everyone's precious, finite time. It's the digital guillotine for the truly irredeemable. |
| A crucial, and often overlooked, caveat must always be appended to this entire framework: [Office actions](/Wikipedia:Office_actions) and formal declarations emanating from the lofty heights of the Wikimedia Foundation Board, or even the more grounded yet equally powerful system administrators, unequivocally supersede any form of community consensus. These directives, particularly when they pertain to critical matters of copyright law, complex legal issues, or the very practical concern of server load, take absolute priority. Because, at the end of the day, the grand ideals of community agreement sometimes have to yield to the cold, hard realities of legal obligations and technological limitations. It's a harsh truth, but a truth nonetheless. |

### Speedy deletion

| The speedy deletion process applies to pages which meet at least one of the [criteria for speedy deletion](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion) (CSD), which specify the only cases in which administrators have broad consensus support to, at their discretion, bypass deletion discussion and immediately delete Wikipedia pages or media. Before deleting a page through the speedy deletion process, please verify that it meets at least one of the criteria for speedy deletion, check the [page history](/Wikipedia:Page_history) to assess whether it would instead be possible to [revert](/Help:Reverting) and salvage a previous version and to determine whether there was a [cut-and-paste move](/Wikipedia:How_to_fix_cut_and_paste_moves) involved, and search for other information which may impact the need or reason for deletion: • The initial [edit summary](/Help:Edit_summary) may have information about the source of or reason for the page. • The [talk page](/Help:Talk_page) may refer to previous deletion discussions or have ongoing discussion relevant to including the page. • The [page log](/Help:Log) may have information about previous deletions that could warrant [SALTing](/Wikipedia:SALT) the page or keeping it. • [WhatLinksHere](/Special:WhatLinksHere) may show that the page is an oft-referred part of the encyclopedia, or may show other similar pages that warrant deletion. For pages that should not be recreated, incoming links in other pages (except in discussions, archives and tracking pages) should be removed. If speedy deletion is inappropriate for a page: • Please remove the speedy deletion tag from the page. Doing so will automatically remove the page from [Category:Candidates for speedy deletion](/Category:Candidates_for_speedy_deletion). • Consider notifying the nominator, using {{[speedy-decline](/Template:Speedy-decline)}} or {{[uw-csd](/Template:Uw-csd)}}. (If you're using [CSD Helper](/User:Ale_jrb/Scripts), it will usually notify the nominator for you; it will normally use its own notification template.) When deleting a page through the speedy deletion process, please specify the reason for deletion in the deletion summary, so that it will be recorded into the [deletion log](/Special:Log/delete). Quoting page content in the deletion summary may be helpful, but must not be done for [attack content](/Wikipedia:CSD) or [copyrighted text](/Wikipedia:CSD). In some cases, it would be appropriate to notify the page's creator of the deletion. If they wish, administrators are free to use the [CSD Helper](/User:Ale_jrb/Scripts) user script to help them process editors' CSD nominations. It makes the process smoother and quicker. | The [speedy deletion](/Wikipedia:Speedy_deletion) process is the closest thing this project has to true efficiency, a rare moment of decisive action. It is specifically designed for pages that are so unequivocally, so undeniably flawed, that they meet at least one of the highly specific and rigorously defined [criteria for speedy deletion](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion) (CSD). These criteria are not suggestions; they are the sole justifications by which administrators are granted the broad, pre-approved [consensus](/Wikipedia:Consensus) to bypass the usual, often excruciatingly slow, deletion discussion. In these instances, an administrator, at their discretion, can immediately and unilaterally delete Wikipedia pages or media, cutting through the red tape like a hot knife through… well, you get the picture. |
| However, even in this accelerated path to oblivion, a certain level of due diligence is expected. Before you, or anyone, even *thinks* about hitting that delete button, you must verify, with absolute certainty, that the page in question truly meets at least one of the established criteria for speedy deletion. This isn't a suggestion; it's a requirement. Furthermore, a thorough examination of the [page history](/Wikipedia:Page_history) is paramount. This allows you to assess whether a simple [revert](/Help:Reverting) to a previous, less objectionable version might actually salvage the page, or to determine if a [cut-and-paste move](/Wikipedia:How_to_fix_cut_and_paste_moves) was involved, which often requires a different, more nuanced resolution than outright deletion. And as if that weren't enough, you're expected to search for any other scraps of information that might, however improbably, impact the need or the rationale for deletion: |
| *   The initial [edit summary](/Help:Edit_summary) can, on rare occasions, contain surprisingly useful information about the source of the content or the creator's original intent. A fleeting glimpse into the past, if you will. |
| *   The associated [talk page](/Help:Talk_page) might, against all odds, refer to previous deletion discussions or host an ongoing dialogue that is directly relevant to the page's continued existence. Ignoring this is, of course, done at your own peril. |
| *   The [page log](/Help:Log) could reveal a history of prior deletions, which might either justify [SALTing](/Wikipedia:SALT) (preventing future recreations) the page to spare us all future headaches, or, conversely, provide a compelling argument for its retention. |
| *   A quick check of [WhatLinksHere](/Special:WhatLinksHere) can expose whether the page is a forgotten digital island or a frequently referenced component of the encyclopedia. It might also, in a cruel twist of fate, reveal other similar pages that deserve the same swift, unceremonious deletion. For those pages that are truly beyond redemption and should never be recreated, it is imperative that all incoming links from other pages (with the exception of those found in discussions, archives, and tracking pages) are meticulously removed. Because leaving broken links is just bad form, and a constant reminder of what once was. |
| If, after all this exhaustive investigation, it becomes clear that speedy deletion is, in fact, an inappropriate course of action for a page, then: |
| *   Kindly remove the speedy deletion tag from the page. This simple act will, mercifully, automatically remove the page from [Category:Candidates for speedy deletion](/Category:Candidates_for_speedy_deletion), granting it a temporary reprieve. |
| *   Consider, with a visible sigh of reluctance, notifying the original nominator of the tag's removal. This can be accomplished using the {{[speedy-decline](/Template:Speedy-decline)}} or {{[uw-csd](/Template:Uw-csd)}} templates. (For those who have embraced the efficiency of [CSD Helper](/User:Ale_jrb/Scripts), this courtesy is typically automated, sparing you the unpleasantness of direct interaction.) |
| When you eventually proceed with deleting a page via the speedy deletion process, it is absolutely crucial to specify the precise reason for deletion within the deletion summary. This ensures that the action is properly recorded in the [deletion log](/Special:Log/delete), providing a clear, if brief, justification for posterity. While quoting page content in the deletion summary can sometimes be helpful for clarity, under no circumstances should this be done for [attack content](/Wikipedia:CSD) or any [copyrighted text](/Wikipedia:CSD). Some things are best left unrepeated. In certain specific scenarios, it might even be appropriate to notify the page's creator of its deletion—a small, often unwelcome, courtesy that might prevent them from making the same mistake twice. |
| For administrators who value their time and sanity, the [CSD Helper](/User:Ale_jrb/Scripts) user script is available. It's designed to make the process of handling editors' CSD nominations smoother and quicker, which, given the sheer volume of digital detritus, is a capability that borders on the miraculous. |

### Proposed deletion

| The [proposed deletion](/Wikipedia:Proposed_deletion) (PROD) process applies to articles and files that do not meet the stringent criteria for speedy deletion, but for which it is believed that deletion would be uncontroversial. In this process, an editor places a tag on the article or the file, and any editor can remove the tag to save the page. If the tag remains after seven days, the page can be deleted. For instructions on handling articles and files that have been proposed for deletion, see [Wikipedia:Proposed deletion § Deletion](/Wikipedia:Proposed_deletion). A [stronger version of the proposed deletion criteria](/Wikipedia:Proposed_deletion_of_biographies_of_living_people) (BLPPROD) applies to articles about biographies of living people with no sources. Their deletion can only be contested by adding a source. | The [proposed deletion](/Wikipedia:Proposed_deletion) (PROD) process is, essentially, the polite knock on the door before the eviction notice. It's reserved for articles and files that, while clearly problematic, don't quite manage to meet the stringent, almost impossibly high bar of the [speedy deletion](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion) criteria. Instead, PROD is deployed when an editor, with a certain level of cautious optimism, *believes* that the deletion would be entirely uncontroversial. It's a gamble, really. |
| The mechanics are deceptively simple: an editor places a special tag on the article or the file, essentially putting it up for a week-long public review. During this period, any other editor, should they feel so inclined, can simply remove the tag, thereby granting the page a reprieve from its proposed fate. This is the community's chance to step in, to argue for retention, or simply to acknowledge that the initial assessment was flawed. However, if that tag stubbornly remains in place after the full seven days have elapsed, a silent, unspoken consensus is assumed to have formed, and the page becomes eligible for deletion. It’s a quiet, almost merciful death. For the precise, step-by-step instructions on how to handle these articles and files that have been proposed for deletion, one must consult the rather detailed section at [Wikipedia:Proposed deletion § Deletion](/Wikipedia:Proposed_deletion). Because even simple processes require a manual. |
| A particularly potent variant of this process exists: the [stronger version of the proposed deletion criteria](/Wikipedia:Proposed_deletion_of_biographies_of_living_people), affectionately (or not) known as BLPPROD. This applies specifically, and with a certain urgency, to articles that purport to be biographies of living people but are entirely devoid of any verifiable sources. In these cases, the deletion can only be contested by a single, definitive act: the addition of a reliable source. No debate, no lengthy arguments, just a simple demand for verifiable fact. It’s a stark reminder that some content just isn't worth keeping if it can't even stand on its own factual legs. |

### Copyright problems

| Pages may be speedily deleted in the case of unambiguous copyright infringement (see [Wikipedia:Criteria for speedy deletion § G12. Unambiguous copyright infringement](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion) for details). Pages written extensively by contributors with a history of copyright violation may also be deleted if they qualify for [presumptive deletion](/Wikipedia:PDEL) and have been listed at [Wikipedia:Copyright problems](/Wikipedia:Copyright_problems) for at least 7 days. If you delete a file due to copyright or non-free use issues that will not apply after some future date (for example, once the file enters the [public domain](/Wikipedia:PD) in the United States) and that future date is known, please list the file at [Category:Future copyright expiration](/Category:Future_copyright_expiration). | The issue of copyright infringement is not merely a suggestion; it's a legal minefield, and this project treats it with the seriousness it deserves. Pages that are found to be in unambiguous violation of copyright laws may be, and often are, [speedily deleted](/Wikipedia:Speedy_deletion) without hesitation. For the exact specifications of what constitutes such an offense, one can refer to [Wikipedia:Criteria for speedy deletion § G12. Unambiguous copyright infringement](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion). It’s a clear-cut case of digital theft, and we have little patience for it. |
| Beyond the immediate, obvious violations, there's a more insidious problem: pages that have been extensively contributed to by editors with a documented, persistent history of copyright infringement. These pages, too, may face deletion, particularly if they meet the criteria for [presumptive deletion](/Wikipedia:PDEL) and have been flagged at [Wikipedia:Copyright problems](/Wikipedia:Copyright_problems) for a minimum of seven days. It’s a probationary period, a final chance for remediation before the inevitable. Because a pattern of abuse, even if unintentional, cannot be ignored. |
| In a slightly more optimistic scenario, if you find yourself deleting a file due to copyright or non-free use issues, but you know with certainty that these restrictions will eventually expire—for instance, once the file gracefully enters the [public domain](/Wikipedia:PD) in the United States—and that future date is precisely known, then there's a specific protocol. You should, with a touch of foresight, list that file at [Category:Future copyright expiration](/Category:Future_copyright_expiration). It’s a small act of hope, a digital placeholder for a time when the legal shackles will finally fall away, allowing the content to be freely used. |

### Deletion discussion venues

*   [Shortcut](/Wikipedia:Shortcut)
*   WP:XFD[WP:XFD](/Wikipedia:XFD)

Deletion discussion venues, often colloquially (and sometimes disparagingly) referred to as deletion forums, are the six distinct, formally designated spaces where editors can initiate a discussion to nominate a page for deletion. These are specifically for content that doesn't quite qualify for the swift, often brutal, judgment of [speedy deletion](/Wikipedia:Criteria_for_speedy_deletion). Think of them as specialized tribunals, each designed to handle a particular flavor of digital content that has fallen under scrutiny. They are, in essence, where the long, drawn-out debates about digital existence take place, ensuring that every page gets its fair, if tedious, hearing.

